   (Message) The program crashes due to a heap-buffer-overflow in `crc8()` when
   it reads one byte past the end of the input buffer. The error arises because
   the loop in `crc8()` uses `i <= len` as its continuation condition, which
   means it iterates `len + 1` times. Since `len` is the size of the buffer (7
   in this case), the loop attempts to access `buf[7]`, which is one byte beyond
   the allocated `buf[7]` array (valid indices 0 to 6). This is a classic off-
   by-one error due to an inclusive upper bound in the loop condition, causing a
   buffer overflow that AddressSanitizer detects.
   
   ROOT CAUSE: `program.c:11` — The loop `for (size_t i = 0; i <= len; i++)`
   uses an inclusive upper bound (`<= len`), causing the loop to iterate one
   time too many and access `buf[len]`, which is one byte past the end of the
   input buffer. This happens because the function `crc8` receives `len` as the
   number of valid bytes, and the index `i` should only go from 0 to `len - 1`
   inclusive.
   
   LOCAL FIX: `program.c:11` — Change `i <= len` to `i < len` in the for loop of
   `crc8()`. This ensures the loop runs exactly `len` times, accessing only
   valid indices 0 to `len - 1` of the input buffer.
   
   GLOBAL FIX: Modify the `crc8` function’s interface to accept a `const
   uint8_t* buf` and a `size_t len` but enforce, via a static_assert or assert,
   that `len` is the number of valid bytes, and use a bounded view or
   `span`-like type (e.g., `const uint8_t*` + `size_t` wrapped in a safe
   container) to prevent buffer overrun at compile time or runtime. This
   prevents the misuse of `len` as inclusive in the loop and introduces a design
   invariant where the length represents the number of valid bytes.
   
   ROOT CAUSE: `program.c:11` — The loop condition `i <= len` causes the loop to
   access `buf[len]`, which is one past the end of the array, due to an off-by-
   one error; this access triggers a heap-buffer-overflow detected by
   AddressSanitizer when the program runs.
   
   LOCAL FIX: Change `for (size_t i = 0; i <= len; i++)` to `for (size_t i = 0;
   i < len; i++)` in the `crc8` function to ensure only valid indices of the
   buffer are accessed.
   
   GLOBAL FIX: Redesign the API to use a bounded buffer view (e.g., `struct span
   { const uint8_t* data; size_t len; }`) that enforces invariants at compile
   time or via assertions, ensuring the length is always interpreted as the
   count of valid bytes and never includes an offset beyond the data.
